"full_text": "Over the weekend
column5: I met with nonprofit leaders in Arizona who work with victims of domestic violence. Their federal funding is critical
column7: some are being forced to turn people away. This shutdown is hurting our most vulnerable\u2014it has to end. https://t.co/Ja5SFmNfXd"

column4: "full_text": "Thank you to the individuals who joined me this afternoon and spoke so openly and honestly. Thank you for continuing to care and serve
column5: even in the toughest conditions. We are indebted to the work you and countless others do every day."

column4: "full_text": "I\u2019m headed back to Washington tomorrow to share these stories and advocate for the people I heard from today\u2014and the hundreds of thousands of others impacted by this needless shutdown. There\u2019s just no way around it
column5: we have to get our government working again. https://t.co/SgzRDSs0BC"

column4: "full_text": "But they also shared with me their new stark reality: Coming home with no paycheck in sight is hurting their families. Some are considering paying penalties to dip into retirement. Others are concerned about accessing their health care benefits. The effects are serious and real. https://t.co/O4FRQ7dDjc"
"full_text": "Despite the furloughs
column5: despite the low morale for those forced to work without pay\u2014many of these individuals were most upset that the shutdown has stalled or halted the critical services they provide the American people. https://t.co/Fh2TkbV8HO"

column4: "full_text": "Several employees and service providers are looking ahead and realizing that the shutdown will disrupt their work plans and budgets for the rest of the year. The consequences they fear will fall back to our residents: from forgone airport safety trainings to wildfire prevention. https://t.co/VoPZOtOBqL"

"full_text": "This afternoon I met with more than a dozen Arizonans affected by the government shutdown. Each described to me the ways in which they feel held hostage each day this shutdown continues\u2014their stories were both heartbreaking and frustrating. https://t.co/IWRc0JHyJY"
"full_text": "Next week
column5: I will once again vote to re-open the government. We will continue to put forward constructive
column6: reasonable and bipartisan solutions to end the shutdown and get our government working again for the American people."

column4: "full_text": "Nearly 90 percent of @DHSgov employees\u2014those on the front lines\u2014are working without pay. 53
column9: 000 Coast Guard active duty members. It\u2019s immoral and it puts our safety at risk."

column4: "full_text": "The @USEEOC\u2014the agency that makes sure employees are protected from race
column7: sexual orientation or gender discrimination\u2014is closed. Mediations have been cancelled and pending cases are being suspended."

column4: "full_text": "Thousands of federal employees responsible for enforcing public health
column6: consumer rights and environmental laws are on furlough. Food safety is at risk
column7: and the shutdown is creating a backlog of approvals for new innovative prescription drugs and medical devices."

column4: "full_text": "E-Verify has been unavailable during the shutdown
column6: 000 private sector employers who rely on the service can\u2019t use it to hire new workers and fill jobs. That\u2019s just plain harmful to our economy."

column4: "full_text": "Most immigration judges are on furlough. Cases are essentially frozen. Our courts are already facing a massive backlog of 800
column6: with new ones now rescheduled several years out. Considering the president\u2019s posture on border security

column4: "full_text": "Grant payments from @TheJusticeDept are now in jeopardy. Domestic violence shelters across the nation\u2014many of which rely on federal grant funds each month\u2014could struggle to keep their doors open and be forced to turn away women and children."
"full_text": "We\u2019re about to enter the second month of this needless shutdown. Tomorrow
column5: I\u2019ll meet with people in AZ who are directly feeling the negative impacts. But I want to take a moment to share how the shutdown\u2019s effect on law enforcement and safety organizations is hurting people."

column4: "full_text": "Two great assignments for working on issues that matter to the future of Arizona. I look forward to working with communities across the state to deliver results on the Transportation & Infrastructure and Judiciary committees. https://t.co/b8NPYEqSIM"

"full_text": "Honored to learn this evening that I\u2019ll be serving on the House Judiciary Committee\u2014a key assignment for Arizona as we work to reform our nation\u2019s broken immigration system. I\u2019m excited to get to work."
"full_text": "24 days of this shutdown has left many American families wondering how they will cover their basic costs of living. We\u2019ve heard from a number of residents feeling scared and hurt
column5: and who are asking us to restore certainty to their lives. Enough is enough. #EndTheShutdown"

column4: "full_text": "We got to work on day one to re-open the government and get it working again for the American people. And we wasted no time our first week
"full_text": "Eight years after Tucson
column5: we'll do more than hold a moment of silence. Today we offer a bill to require universal background checks for gun sales. I'm proud to stand with @GabbyGiffords
column8: and many more to make this common-sense proposal a reality."
